### Rewriting rational terms as negative powers

$\begin{align}
h(x)&=\dfrac{-4}{x^3}+\dfrac{1}{x}
\\\\
&=-4x^{-3}+x^{-1}
\end{align}$

### Evaluating $h'(x)$

So we found that $h'(x)=\dfrac{12}{x^4}-\dfrac{1}{x^2}$.

Let's plug $x=-2$ into $h'$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}h'(-2)
\\\\
&=\dfrac{12}{(-2)^4}-\dfrac{1}{(-2)^2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{12}{16}-\dfrac{1}{4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{3}{4}-\dfrac{1}{4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2}{4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{2}
\end{align}$

