### Rewriting rational terms as negative powers

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}-\dfrac{1}{x^4}-\dfrac{5}{x^2}
\\\\
&=-x^{-4}-5x^{-2}
\end{align}$

### Differentiating using the power rule

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{d}{dx}(-x^{-4}-5x^{-2}
)
\\\\
&=-1\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-4})-5\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-2})
\\\\
&=-1(-4x^{-5})-5(-2)x^{-3}
\\\\
&=4x^{-5}+10x^{-3}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{4}{x^5}+\dfrac{10}{x^3}
\end{align}$

### Evaluating the derivative

So we found that $\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(-\dfrac{1}{x^4}-\dfrac{5}{x^2}\right)=\dfrac{4}{x^5}+\dfrac{10}{x^3}$.

Let's evaluate it at $x=2$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{4}{x^5}+\dfrac{10}{x^3}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{4}{(2)^5}+\dfrac{10}{(2)^3}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{4}{32}+\dfrac{10}{8}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{8}+\dfrac{10}{8}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{11}{8}
\end{align}$

### Rewriting rational terms as negative powers

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{9}{x^3}+\dfrac{1}{x}
\\\\
&=9x^{-3}+x^{-1}
\end{align}$

### Differentiating using the power rule

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{d}{dx}(9x^{-3}+x^{-1}
)
\\\\
&=9\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-3})+\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-1})
\\\\
&=9(-3x^{-4})+(-1)x^{-2}
\\\\
&=-27x^{-4}-1x^{-2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{27}{x^4}-\dfrac{1}{x^2}
\end{align}$

### Evaluating the derivative

So we found that $\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\dfrac{9}{x^3}+\dfrac{1}{x}\right)=-\dfrac{27}{x^4}-\dfrac{1}{x^2}$.

Let's evaluate it at $x=-3$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}-\dfrac{27}{x^4}-\dfrac{1}{x^2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{27}{(-3)^4}-\dfrac{1}{(-3)^2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{27}{81}-\dfrac{1}{9}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{3}{9}-\dfrac{1}{9}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{4}{9}
\end{align}$

