### Rewriting rational terms as negative powers

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}-\dfrac{1}{x^2}-\dfrac{7}{x}
\\\\
&=-x^{-2}-7x^{-1}
\end{align}$

### Differentiating using the power rule

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{d}{dx}(-x^{-2}-7x^{-1}
)
\\\\
&=-1\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-2})-7\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-1})
\\\\
&=-1(-2x^{-3})-7(-1)x^{-2}
\\\\
&=2x^{-3}+7x^{-2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2}{x^3}+\dfrac{7}{x^2}
\end{align}$

### Evaluating the derivative

So we found that $\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(-\dfrac{1}{x^2}-\dfrac{7}{x}\right)=\dfrac{2}{x^3}+\dfrac{7}{x^2}$.

Let's evaluate it at $x=-2$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{2}{x^3}+\dfrac{7}{x^2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2}{(-2)^3}+\dfrac{7}{(-2)^2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{2}{8}+\dfrac{7}{4}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{1}{4}+\dfrac{7}{4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{6}{4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{3}{2}
\end{align}$

